# ⭐ **SUMMARY: Hardware in the Advanced Propellants Ops Hub**

The hardware domain is the **backbone** of your system. Every other domain (Procedures, TestOps, Safety, Documents) attaches to hardware in some way, so this conceptual model is foundational.

Below is everything we’ve developed so far.

---

# 1. **Purpose of the Hardware Domain**

The hardware portion of the site acts as the authoritative source of truth for:

* What hardware exists
* Its identity (HYYXXX)
* Its current state (location, custodian, status)
* Its safety context (hazards, propellant/media, pressure/temperature ratings)
* Its operational history (cleaning, tests, servicing, calibrations)
* Its relationships (assemblies, children, mates, related parts)
* Its documents (drawings, travelers, test reports)
* Its pedigree (the complete history of what has been done to it)

In other words:

> **Hardware holds the identity and lineage for every physical object the lab touches.**

---

# 2. **Key Concept: Hardware as a Hub Object**

Hardware is not passive. It is connected to:

* **Procedures** (which apply to it)
* **Procedure Runs** (as-run logs)
* **Small Tests**
* **Test Campaigns**
* **Calibration records**
* **Service records**
* **Travelers**
* **Safety documents**
* **Drawings and schematics**

This creates the hardware’s **pedigree**, essential for both flight and dev work.

---

# 3. **Full Conceptual Field Set for Hardware**

These are the **key fields** — the essential data you need to store for each hardware item. They define what the hardware table *is*.

### **IDENTITY**

* `hardware_id` (HYYXXX — primary identity)
* `description`
* `category` (valve, thruster, sensor, tool, fixture, HX, etc.)
* `classification` (development, flight, flight-spare, GSE, retired)

### **DETAILS**

* `serial_number` (optional)
* `part_number` (optional)
* `manufacturer` (optional)
* `date_added`

### **STATUS & LIFECYCLE**

* `status` (`in-service`, `awaiting-inspection`, `under-test`, `retired`, etc.)
* `lifecycle_stage` (`new`, `as-received`, `cleaned`, etc.)
* `date_status_updated`
* `disposition_notes`

### **LOCATION & CUSTODY**

* `location` (“Lab A rack 3”, etc.)
* `custodian`
* `facility` (optional)
* `loan_status` (`loaned-out`, `in-lab`)
* `loan_to` / loan notes (optional)

### **SAFETY CONTEXT**

* `safety_class` (`pressure`, `cryo`, `flammable`, `high-temp`, etc.)
* `propellant_or_media` (`AF-M315E`, `H₂O₂ 90%`, GN₂, etc.)
* `max_rated_pressure`
* `max_rated_temperature`

### **RELATIONSHIPS (other objects pointing here)**

Conceptually (these will often be join tables later):

* Linked **Procedures** (which SOPs apply)
* Linked **Procedure Runs** (cleaning, decontam, assembly steps)
* Linked **Small Tests**
* Linked **Test Campaigns**
* Linked **Calibration records**
* Linked **Service records**

All of these build the hardware **pedigree**.

### **DOCUMENT LINKS**

Metadata references to:

* Drawings
* Schematics
* Test reports
* Travelers
* Calibration certs
* Safety docs

Actual files live **outside** the system — the Ops Hub only holds the metadata + link.

